pull_request.body:
<!-- markdownlint-disable MD012 -->

<!--
Set the PR title to a meaningful commit message that:

* is in imperative form.
* follows the Conventional Commits specification (https://www.conventionalcommits.org).
  * See https://github.com/commitizen/conventional-commit-types/blob/master/index.json for possible
    types.

Example:

fix: Don't add implicit wildcards ('*') at the beginning and the end of a query (fixes #390).
-->

# Description

<!-- Describe what this request will change/fix and provide any details necessary for reviewers. -->

## References

* This PR is one of the PR series #840.
* This PR depends on #882.

## Overview

This PR integrates `QueryHandler` into `Deserializer`. `QueryHandler` is added as a templated parameter to `Deserializer`, where it can be an instance of `clp::ffi::ir_stream::search::QueryHandler` as introduced in the previous PRs in this series, or `clp::ffi::ir_stream::search::EmptyQueryHandler` (an empty class) to perform no query handling. This design ensures the type/functionality of a deserializer is determined statically: it's either designed to read the entire stream, or is configured to read the stream with KQL query filtering or column projections.

The factory function of the deserializer is templated to have two different versions:
- The first one takes no query handler (which preserves the existing API). The constructed deserializer behaves in the same way as before this PR.
- The second one explicitly takes a query handler, which returns a deserializer with query handler support.

The C++ typing system will treat the deserializers above as different types. However, if users use the `auto` keyword for creation, the type can be automatically deduced according to the chosen factory function.

# Checklist

issue.title: Add update method to foods
issue.body:
Replace the manual rendering of the foods in the main.py file with a dedicated `update` method in the food class, something like:
```python
class Food:
    def update(self, dispaly, deltaTime) -> None:
        """Method called every frame"""
        self.render(display)
        # or manually
        display.blit(...)
```
And then, in the main.py script, call update every frame
```python
# in the main loop
for food in self.foods:
    food.update(self.display, deltaTime)
```

issue.title: Crater Mapgen causes a lot of errors and visibly slows down my game

labels.name: (S2 - Confirmed)
labels.description: Bug that's been confirmed to exist

issue.body:
### Describe the bug

I was travelling down a road when I noticed that the road was spilt in half by a massive series of craters.
I assume that I can just easily drive around it, and so I move closer.
I was instead bombarded by errors, and my game visibly lags as I move closer.

### Attach save file

[test_copy-trimmed.tar.gz](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19088209/test_copy-trimmed.tar.gz)

### Steps to reproduce

With my save:

1. Load the save.
2. Walk North
3. Have your screen fill with errors

Without my save:
1. Create new world.
2. Find the nearest cluster of craters
3. Approach it
4. Have your screen fill with errors

### Expected behavior

I expected for my screen to not be bombarded with mapgen errors
I also expected for my game to not lag when I approach the craters, but I understand that's because of the explosions and that there's not much to do here other than wait for all the explosions to finish exploding.

### Screenshots

Where the save loads:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b152bf8a-51be-449e-99e0-dee97ecab30f)
